AGENTIC-VT 1.0

[metadata]
title: What Happened to Freegen? The most amazing thing ever. See Part1 of Motor Magic
channel: @octopusinc_
source: https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=OFjPJYMqb8Q
upload_date: 20260622
transcript_source: captions
route: text

---

[00:12] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'As you can see, we\'re long overdue to share an update on where this Freegen motor project is at that we first announced or talked about 2 years ago in 2024. And the good news is there\'s been an enormous amount of exciting development in those past few years, which we\'ll talk about right now. So, to'

[00:25] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'recap quickly, Freegen was a very clever and brilliant idea that an inventor Elon Goldman had to mount the disc rotor of a hub motor e-bike onto the planet gears instead of mounting the disc rotor'

[00:38] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'directly to the hub shell. What this enabled is an elegant solution that allowed the geared motor to freewheel effortlessly when you\'re just pedaling the bike without the motor and have no drag, but they would automatically switch into regenerative braking mode'

[00:51] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'whenever you squeeze the brake lever. It seamlessly incorporated your existing mechanical brakes to activate regenerative braking inside the wheel. Now, there\'s many more layers of genius to this idea that are discussed in detail in that last video release, but'

[01:04] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'that\'s the essence. &gt;&gt; I I tip my hat to you. That\'s the most brilliant idea I\'ve seen in a long time. &gt;&gt; It wasn\'t too long after that video release that Elon came to Vancouver to spend some time here at Grin and actually help us build and fabricate possible production-ready prototypes of'

[01:18] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'this motor system. And the result of that very productive week is what you see here. This is a Shengyi motor that\'s our favorite small geared hub motor, runs totally silent with its helical gears. It\'s been modified so that again,'

[01:31] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'the disc rotor\'s connected to the planet gears and it stops by Freegen braking. We have this set up on a semi-recumbent bike e-bike and that was my main commuter for several months. The system also is wired up to use our existing'

[01:44] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Phase Runner motor controllers, but because of the advanced controls needed to modulate that regen braking force, the controller is being run in a digital control mode. So, So created what we called tentatively the super-duper harness as this interface device where'

[01:57] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'all the intelligent advanced algorithm existed and that would command the Phase Runner motor controller appropriately to get that free gen behavior. The system really worked great, but sadly for Grin,'

[02:09] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'we weren\'t in a good position for putting much effort into additional R&amp;D and development work. But fortunately for Elan and Charge Bike, they had other commercial clients who expressed a huge interest in this product and were able to continue the funding and development'

[02:21] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'in the meantime. And that\'s where things get a bit interesting. So you see, it wasn\'t too long after we had this mock-up here in Vancouver that some staff and local people at Grin recognized that, "Hey, if instead of mounting the disc to the planet carrier,'

[02:34] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'they flip that around to mount the pedal system to the planet carrier, you could actually have something like an ECVT where your pedal speed becomes decoupled from the speed of the bicycle." &gt;&gt; It originally had a free gen setup with'

[02:46] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'a brake rotor here with a free gen regenerative braking. But we laser cut a sprocket and installed it instead of the brake rotor. So the sprocket has a six-bolt mounting pattern and the'

[02:58] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'sprocket is directly bolted to the planet carrier. So I\'m pedaling at a certain cadence, right? And I\'m going this speed. And now if I speed up, I\'m going way faster same cadence.'

[03:11] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: '&gt;&gt; So little did we know here at Grin, at the same time Elan was actually working on this exact same development with his commercial clients in a project that they were dubbing Magic Drive. [music] So what happens when you mount the drive'

[03:27] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'system of the bike to the planet carrier instead of directly to the hub? Well, it turns out a lot more than just this ECVT. So to fully understand all the capabilities that this approach gives, it\'s important that we first really wrap'

[03:40] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'our head around the mechanics of what\'s going on. So to start off with, let\'s imagine that we\'ve mounted the cog of our bike to the planet carrier like this, but we\'ve electronically locked the motor. So the motor itself is not able to spin. Now, as we turn the pedals, the chain\'s going'

[03:54] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'to spin the cog. The cog rotates the planet carrier, and that spins the ring gear of the hub, and the entire hub rotates. It looks like it\'s about a one-to-one ratio, but it\'s actually a bit higher than that. Typically, 1.2:1 for a typical gear system in a motor,'

[04:07] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'and that would feel like you\'re just riding a bike with a internal gear hub that has a slightly higher than one-to-one gear. Now, let\'s imagine the total inverse of that. Instead of us pedaling with the motor locked, let\'s lock our pedals so'

[04:19] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'that we\'re not spinning the cranks at all, and instead drive the motor. Well, with the pedals locked, the planet carrier can\'t rotate, and now when the motor spins, it\'s driving the ring gear through the planet gears at the normal gears-motor ratio. And that would cause'

[04:32] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'the motor to spin forwards exactly the same speed as it would in a typical geared motor, where the planet carrier is just not spinning. So, now it should be easy to imagine what\'s going to happen if you both pedal and motor at the same time.'

[04:45] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'If you\'re pedaling at an equivalent rate to move the bike at 10 km/h, but now add the motor spinning at a speed that would move the bike at 20 km/h, the end result is that this bike is going to travel at'

[04:57] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: '30 km/h. The speed output of the hub is just the sum of the speeds that your pedaling\'s contributing, plus the speed that the motor\'s producing. If either the motor speed increases or your pedal speed increases, then the wheel speed'

[05:09] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'will increase in proportion as well. Now, as the bike speeds up, if your pedal speed stays the same, the motor has to keep going at a faster and faster RPM. And the result of that is the motor doing a larger and larger share of the'

[05:21] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'work. Suppose your pedaling is doing 10 km/h, and the motor\'s doing 20, well, the motor\'s doing 2/3 of the work, and your pedaling is doing 1/3 of the watts. The power split between the human and the motor is exactly the same as the'

[05:34] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'speed split in their contribution to the total bike speed. So, suppose I decide to pedal harder and spin the cranks faster, so my pedal speed is now 15 km an hour, but the'

[05:46] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'motor slows down so that my bike speed stays the same and the motor\'s also moving at 15. Well, now we just have a 50/50 power split between my legs and the motor contributing to the bike moving at that 30 clicks.'

[05:59] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'So, you can see the temptation to call this an ECVT or an electronic variable transmission because it allows me to independently vary my pedal speed regardless of how fast the bicycle'

[06:11] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'itself is moving. The motor can make up the difference in speed between my pedals and the wheel. But, it\'s not really a variable transmission in that in a transmission, if I change my gear ratio, I\'m also changing my torque'

[06:23] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'coupling. When I go to an easy gear, I have less torque on the pedals. A harder gear is more torque on the pedals. In this situation, the torque remains exactly the same no matter what my equivalent gear ratio is. Having the motor spin faster doesn\'t change the'

[06:36] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'torque of the crank at all. All it changes is the speed that my crank is spinning at. So, let\'s talk a little more about torque because that\'s a really unique aspect of this setup. Because both the'

[06:49] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'pedals and the motor are driving through the same transmission, they always have to be producing the exact same torque output. If you imagine a situation where I\'m just sitting on the bike and I hit a throttle, well, now the motor\'s'

[07:01] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'producing this torque, the planet gears have to react against that, so I will feel the motor torque on the pedal. The harder I push the throttle, the more the pedal\'s going to want to spin backwards. If I don\'t apply that torque with my legs, say I just take my legs off the'

[07:14] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'cranks, well, then the pedals will just freely spin in reverse and the bike won\'t go anywhere. You have to react with the pedals at the same force that the motor produces. By a similar token, whatever force I\'m putting on the pedals'

[07:26] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'while I\'m riding, the motor has to immediately mirror and match that torque. If I push harder on the cranks and the motor didn\'t increase its torque output, the cranks would just slip. You\'re having two things pushing against'

[07:38] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'each other, but if one is pushing harder than the other, it will immediately accelerate over in one direction. So, with this mounting topology, the motor torque and the pedal torque are always one in the same. &gt;&gt; [music]'

[07:52] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: '&gt;&gt; So, there\'s a nice analogy we can make here to series parallel wiring in electrical circuits. In a typical hub motor drive, the speed of the motor and the speed of your pedaling are in parallel. That is,'

[08:04] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'whatever speed the motor\'s at, the pedals have to be at that same speed. If, say, you\'re pedaling at a slower speed than the motor spinning in the hub, you\'re just not going to be doing anything. And if you were to pedal at a faster speed than the motor, then you'

[08:16] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'end up doing all the work. In that shared power situation, the motor RPM and the pedal RPM to the wheel always match. But, the torques of the motors are added up in series. So, if the motor\'s doing 40 Newton meters, my'

[08:28] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'pedals are doing 20 Newton meters, then the rear wheel gets the sum of those two things, in this case, 60 Newton meters of torque. The torque that\'s experienced at the wheel is just the sum of the motor torque plus the pedal torque. With this magic drive, we have the exact'

[08:42] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'inverse of that situation. In this case, the speeds are added in series, but the torques are in parallel and always have to match. &gt;&gt; [music] &gt;&gt; So, I\'m sure a number of you are sitting'

[08:56] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'there watching this thinking, "Well, duh, we\'ve seen this before. That\'s exactly like the power split device in a Toyota hybrid drive that\'s been around for decades. This isn\'t new. You\'re just applying an existing idea or concept to an e-bike that\'s already well'

[09:09] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'established in automotive and other worlds." And that is completely correct. And in fact, power split devices on bicycles aren\'t entirely new, either. We found literature and papers talking about this kind of concept in the 1990s. There\'s patents in the early or mid'

[09:23] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: '2000s, 2010s. And there\'s even products on the market, like the Awurudu drive that\'s in the Decathlon e-bike sold in Europe, that have very much the same power split topology, but built inside the bottom bracket of a drive.'

[09:36] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'What\'s unique and different here is implementing all of that inside a hub motor and doing it in a way that\'s using off-the-shelf existing hub motor components. And putting it in the hub does bring'

[09:48] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'about a lot of unique capabilities. So, let\'s talk about some of these extra features. So, the most obvious benefit here is getting rid of the gears. Now, as we say, it\'s not truly an ECVT in'

[10:01] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'that you\'re not changing the transmission of your pedal torque effort. If you\'re going up a hill, you do need to put more torque on the pedals because the motor itself needs to produce more torque and the torque of the motor and the pedals are always'

[10:14] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'linked, but you have fully decoupled your pedal cadence from the bike speed. So, you don\'t have to have a whole set of gears, a derailleur, and a shifter in order to pedal comfortably at a low speed or at high S pedal act speeds. Getting rid of derailleurs, cable'

[10:28] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'guides, shifters reduces the cost of a bicycle build, and most importantly, it makes cycling a lot more accessible to people who are just not tuned into the mechanics of riding a bike. Basically, anyone can hop on a bike with this magic'

[10:40] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'drive installed, and you just pedal it. You don\'t have to know anything about upshifting or downshifting or changing gears before you come to a stop. &gt;&gt; [music] &gt;&gt; But, one of the other great features of'

[10:53] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'this implementation is regenerative braking control. Because the motor torque matches the pedal torque, if you put a reverse torque on the pedals, well, the motor has to mirror that and start doing regenerative braking. So, in the control system that we have where'

[11:07] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'your forwards pedaling is governed to a fixed pedal cadence, the reverse mode, once it senses your pedaling backwards, it locks the pedals in their fixed position and it keeps varying the motor torque to keep your pedals from moving.'

[11:19] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'The harder you push backwards on the cranks, the more the motor does regen. You come to a stop feeling just like you\'re a coaster brake experience from a kid with all that energy going back into the battery pack. So, while this coaster brake mode is'

[11:35] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'really cool, it does require actually quite some effort on the legs if you really want to come to a quick stop, because to get the motor to do its maximum torque, your pedals have to do an enormous torque as well. And so, it\'s fine for slowing down in general, the'

[11:48] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'more panic stop scenario is really better served by something that can apply a greater amount of regen. Now, quite uniquely, there\'s nothing stopping us from also mounting the disc rotor on the same side as the drive system. So,'

[12:00] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'if we put a disc rotor on, we still have a free gen system, just like this other setup that we were first working on, where you squeeze your brakes, that lets you put an enormous torque on the planet carrier, the motor matches that with its'

[12:12] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'regen, and you can come to a very sudden stop without any extra effort needed on the legs. So, this next feature is especially cool'

[12:24] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'on tricycle and quad builds, even if it\'s rather useless on a two-wheel bike. And that\'s the ability to mirror this behavior so that you can pedal in reverse, too. There\'s nothing inherently forward reverse sensing about mounting the'

[12:37] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'planet gears to the pedal drivetrain, and that enables us to have a special mode in trike and quad vehicles where, when you\'re moving forwards and you push backwards on the pedals, you get this nice coaster brake regen to a stop. But'

[12:49] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'once you\'ve come to a stop, the electronic control can then allow you to actually spin the cranks backwards. It can do this locking the motor so you now have a nice one-to-one pedal mapping to allow you to back up, go forwards, do'

[13:03] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'multi-point turns, all with the convenience and natural extension of your leg turning the crank. There\'s no forward reverse switch on the handlebars, you don\'t have to flintstone your bike to back out of a corner, you just keep your legs on the cranks and'

[13:15] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'pedal so naturally. It comes out so intuitively that you don\'t even think about the incredible mechanics that would be necessary to do that in a traditional system. The next advantage we see here is the'

[13:29] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'total elimination of any need for a pedal torque sensor. In your traditional drive system where the motor and the pedal drivetrain are hooked up independently, if you want to have a proportional control that'

[13:41] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'responds to the pedal effort, you have to add a separate piece of hardware that measures and senses the pedal torque. Those can be strain gauges on the cranks, they can be chain tension sensors, they can be dropout sensor sensors, but there\'s extra cost,'

[13:53] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'complexity, and wiring needed to measure that. In this magic drive topology, no force sensor is needed at all. The motor controller just inherently has to know how much the rider is pedaling because their pedaling torque causes the motor'

[14:05] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'to spin and it responds to that. That reduces the bill of materials and the cost for OEMs building e-bikes and it makes aftermarket installation more straightforward as well. &gt;&gt; [music]'

[14:17] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: '&gt;&gt; And there\'s another capability that\'s perhaps a bit more novelty, but still might find some appeal. And that\'s to have a exercise bike or trainer mode. If you have the wheel locked on the bike'

[14:29] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'and you just spin the pedals, well, you\'re now turning the motor and you have a perfectly controllable generator system. And you can totally hook up your regular bike into any app or control interface that lets you turn it into an exercise bike simulating riding up and'

[14:42] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'down hills and different terrains. It lets you do that with full control over the pedal cadence and have any other variable. And you can do that with the very same bike that you ride as your regular commuter.'

[14:54] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'There\'s another mechanical benefit to this installation that\'s very similar to one of these benefits we talked about in FreeGen, and that\'s the great reduction of needing a torque arm on the motor'

[15:07] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'axle. Because the motor torque is primarily being coupled to the planet gears which are linked to the pedals, your bicycle pedals have now become the torque arm for the motor, which means you can have a very powerful motor without worrying about the axle spinning'

[15:20] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'out inside the dropouts because all of that motor torque is being reacted against from the long torque arm of your pedal cranks up front. And finally, we have the unique'

[15:34] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'retro-fittability of this system. So, in your other power split devices that are based in the bottom bracket, there\'s no way someone can add that to an existing bike that they already have. By doing it inside the motor like this, this is'

[15:46] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'totally retro-fittable on an existing bike. You can take a normal bike frame, simply swap out the hub for this magic drive hub, and now have a full EVT control system. The bottom bracket drive crank sets don\'t change at all. And as'

[16:00] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'with the free jump system, the modifications to off-the-shelf motors to support this kind of drive are really minimal. All we need to do, once again, is bring that planet carrier outside of the hub through a large diameter ball'

[16:14] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'bearing and a custom motor side plate, and now a stock motor has this whole host of new capabilities as long as you have a motor controller that can take advantage of it. So, that\'s it for part one of this video where we\'ve talked'

[16:26] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'about the main key advantages and uniqueness of this magic drive topology. In part two that follows, we\'re going to go into a much more technical and nuanced look about the challenges of implementing the control systems that exist here. We\'re going to talk about'

[16:39] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'throttles and clutches and other ways of controlling this motor that don\'t involve all the torque being linked to the pedals. Uh we\'re going to talk about comparisons between this magic drive and pedal generator systems, which is another'

[16:51] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'approach to having a decoupled pedaling from the bike speed that shares many overlapping capabilities, but also various pros and cons between those two approaches. Uh and we\'re finally going to talk about the various backup modes'

[17:03] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'that can exist that would allow you to keep pedaling the bike with this magic drive even in the event of a complete electronics failure or a totally dead battery pack. So, please stay tuned for part two to release later this summer, and in the'

[17:16] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'meantime, if you\'re interested in checking out this technology, we\'re going to be exhibiting at Eurobike the week of June 24th in Frankfurt. Uh we\'ll have several bikes available both at Grin\'s booth and also on the test track,'

[17:28] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'where you can see firsthand what the experience is like riding with a magic drive system decoupling the pedaling from the vehicle speed. We look forward to seeing some people there and seeing many of you tuned in for the next'

[17:41] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'update. &gt;&gt; [music] &gt;&gt; I was able to parallel park on this'

[18:01] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'thing.'
